Package: RLT

Version: 6.0.2

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Fixed NTest > 1 guard for distribute importance in regression forest build.

Fixed typos in error messages and documentation.

Fixed integer literal 1 -> 1L for .Call fallbacks in all model types.

Cleaned up SurvForest dead code, scalar logic, seq_len, and class vectors.

Fixed classification variance table in README to reflect IJ and jackknife
support.

Removed dead code in C++ (no-op if statements, commented-out barriers).

Updated .gitignore and removed stale v4.2.6 references from README.

All 326 tests passing.

Version: 6.0.1

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Separated split_rule and linear_comb_method into independent PARAM_GLOBAL fields;
previously a single field was overloaded for both purposes.

Removed the reinforcement gate from linear.comb so that linear combination
splits operate independently without requiring embedded model convergence.

Promoted linear.comb, linear.comb.method, and split.rule to top-level R
arguments for direct user control.

Added copyfrom() propagation for linear_comb_method so that child nodes
correctly inherit the parent's linear combination method.

Fixed var_mode storage type from bool to size_t, which was previously
truncating valid values in the 0–3 range.

Survival linear combination splits: added CoxPH loading with support for
observation weights.

Survival linear combination splits: variable screening now respects the
chosen split_rule (logrank versus suplogrank).

Survival: implemented weighted logrank and sup-logrank split rules to
support observation weights.

Survival: implemented categorical splits for the sup-logrank rule.

Survival: added input validation checks for missing values (is.na),
dimensions (dim), types (type), and censoring.

Removed the dead penalty mechanism from survival split rules.

Removed the split_gen parameter from C++ internals, replacing it with
direct nsplit checks.

get.surv.band: replaced the orthoDr/glmnet dependency with mgcv for GAM
smoothing.

get.surv.band: corrected approach names to 'naive' and 'smoothed'.

Fixed README: updated the feature table, test count, and survival
capabilities.

Moved orthoDr and glmnet from Imports to removed since they are no longer
needed.

Version: 6.0.0

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Complete C++ rewrite using the Rcpp/RcppArmadillo backend, replacing the
previous C backend.

OpenMP parallel computing with bit-identical reproducibility across any
number of cores.

xoshiro256+ random number generator for deterministic parallel results.

Linear combination (LC) splits for regression (naive, LM, PCA, SIR) and
classification (LDA, naive, random, logistic).

Survival analysis with three split rules: logrank, sup-logrank, and Cox
gradient.

Variance estimation methods: matched-sample U-statistic, infinitesimal
jackknife, and jackknife-after-bootstrap.

Variable importance variance ($VarVI) estimation.

Classification probability estimation.

get.one.tree() for single tree inspection.

Survival confidence bands via get.surv.band(), with naive and smoothed
approaches.

Observation weights for survival models under logrank and sup-logrank
rules.

Weighted variable sampling (var.prob) via the Efraimidis-Spirakis
algorithm.

Over 490 tests across 15 test files.

Vignettes for regression, classification, and survival.

Version: 5.8.0

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Renamed var.w (variable weights) to var.prob (variable probabilities) across
all models (regression, classification, survival, quantile). The new name
better reflects the intended usage as sampling probabilities for split
variable selection.

Renamed var.ready to var.mode. Now accepts "none" (default) or "matched"
(matched-sample U-statistic decomposition). Specifying var.mode = TRUE is
equivalent to var.mode = "matched". This change makes the interface extensible
for future variance estimation methods.

Added variable importance variance estimation for regression forests. When
var.mode = "matched" and importance is enabled, the returned object includes
$VarVI — a vector of length p containing the variance of each variable's
importance score, computed via the same V_h - V_s U-statistic decomposition
used for prediction variance. Importance is automatically switched to
"distribute" mode when var.mode is active (permutation importance adds extra
variance).

Implemented weighted variable sampling for var.prob: when supplied, mtry
variables are sampled without replacement with probabilities proportional
to the supplied weights. Previously this feature only worked for survival
(as a score penalty); now it works for all models (regression, classification,
survival, quantile) via a new weighted_sample() method in the Rand class
(Efraimidis-Spirakis algorithm). For survival, the existing score penalty
mechanism is preserved alongside the new weighted sampling.

Added compact classification test suite with 11 focused tests covering:
basic fitting, prediction, accuracy, multiclass, categorical predictors,
OOB predictions, variable importance, var.prob, seed reproducibility,
linear combination splits, and edge cases. Additional var.prob tests verify
acceptance for both classification and regression, and confirm that skewed
weights concentrate importance on high-probability variables.

Version: 5.7.0

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Streamlined linear combination (LC) interface:
  - alpha is now a top-level parameter (default 0)
  - split.gen and embed.split.gen removed from user-facing API
  - Auto-derived: nsplit=0 -> best(3), nsplit>0 -> random(1)
  - embed.nsplit allows 0
  - embed.ntrees default changed to 50
  - embed.threshold default set to 0.25
  - LC methods: lda(1), naive(2), random(3), logistic(4)

Fixed check_varw() in R to properly return normalized variable weights.

Tiered LC: switch.size = 3 * embed.nmin.
  Tier 1 (n >= switch.size): full embed + VI + LC
  Tier 2 (n < switch.size): marginal screen -> LC

